        "body": "The transition from cosmological sovereignty (65:5-8) to agricultural providence (65:9-11) is achieved by a single verb: *paqad* — to visit. This is a covenant-historical term of the highest theological density. It appears at Genesis 50:24, where the dying Joseph promises his brothers that God 'will surely visit you' and bring them out of Egypt — a promise Moses echoes in Exodus 3:16. When God visits in the Old Testament, He comes with purposeful, history-changing intention. To say that God visits the earth in verse 9 is to claim that the rainy season is not a meteorological accident but a covenant event — as theologically significant as the Exodus, conducted on a smaller stage.\n\nWhat follows in verses 9-10 is one of the Bible's most detailed meditations on the specific mechanics of divine providence in agriculture. The stream of God is full of water — a reference to the heavenly reservoir (cf. Genesis 7:11's 'floodgates of the sky'; Job 38:37's 'waterskins of the heavens') that God releases over the earth. Then seven consecutive second-person verbs track God's agricultural management: He soaks the furrows (*ravah*), levels the ridges (*nachat*), softens the soil with showers (*mug*, *raviv*), blesses the growth (*barakh tsemach*). The deliberate accumulation of verbs — each naming a different phase of the soil's preparation — dismantles the assumption that agriculture is primarily a human achievement. The farmer plows and plants; God does everything else.\n\nVerse 11 crowns the sequence with royal imagery. *Atar* — to encircle as with a crown — is used of God placing a crown on the year itself. The entire agricultural year from first rains to final harvest is encircled by God's *tov* (bounty, goodness — the same word used of creation's verdict in Genesis 1). And 'Your paths drip with fatness' (*deshen* — the richness of fat, abundance) — wherever God moves through His creation in the course of the year, superabundance falls. The paths He walks drip. This is not the minimal providence of bare sufficiency; it is the extravagant providence of a God who over-delivers.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Paqad* (v.9, 'visit') — the covenant visit-verb of the Exodus tradition; here applied to creation care with full covenantal weight. *Ravah* (v.10) — to drench, to saturate; not mere watering but saturation. *Tov* (v.11, 'bounty') — goodness, pleasantness; the same term as God's verdict on creation in Genesis 1. *Deshen* (v.11, 'fatness') — richness, fattiness, the word for the fat of sacrificial offerings — agricultural abundance is implicitly sacrificial language."
