        "title": "Creation's own doxology — the valleys that shout and the hills that gird themselves with joy",
        "range": "65:12-13",
        "excerpt": "The meadows are clothed with flocks and the valleys are covered with grain; they shout for joy, yes, they sing.",
        "body": "The psalm's final two verses are among the most sustained personifications of creation in the entire Psalter, and their theological function is precise. The movement is from the wilderness margins to the cultivated center: pastures of the *midbar* (wilderness, the uncultivated wild) overflow (65:12); hills gird themselves with rejoicing — the verb *chagar* (to gird) is typically used of a warrior strapping on weapons or a king girding with might (cf. Psalm 18:32; 93:1). Here the hills put on joy as battle-dress. The meadows (*kar* — pastures used for grazing, the landscape of the shepherd) are clothed with flocks; the valleys (*emeq* — the agricultural lowlands) are decked with grain.\n\nThe double clothing image (hills robed in joy, valleys covered in grain, meadows clothed with flocks) is deliberate: abundance is the garment of the created order. Creation wears its harvest as a festival vestment. And the final sentence — 'they shout for joy, yes, they sing' — is the psalm's climactic surprise. Throughout verses 9-12, God has been the subject of virtually every verb. Now the subject shifts to creation itself: it shouts (*rua* — the cultic shout of the congregation, used of Israel's worship in Ezra 3:11-13) and sings (*shir* — the verb of the great songs: Exodus 15, Deborah's song, the Songs of Songs). The meadows and valleys have become a worshiping congregation.\n\nThis is not mere poetic sentiment. Romans 8:19-22 provides the New Testament theological key: creation 'waits eagerly for the revealing of the sons of God' and is 'subjected to futility' under the curse of Genesis 3:17-18. Paul's language of creation's eager expectation and groaning is intelligible only if Psalm 65:13's vision of creation's praise is the eschatological goal — what creation was made for and what it will ultimately achieve at the consummation. Psalm 65 gives that future its present tense: in the harvest season, creation's praise breaks through proleptically.\n\nThe structural arc of the psalm is now complete. It opened with *dumiyyah* — silence, the congregation struck speechless before God (65:1). It closes with *shir* — song, the created order raising its voice in full-throated praise (65:13). The God who atones for the transgressions that silence human worship (65:3) is the God who, through the same sovereign provision that visits the furrows and crowns the year (65:9-11), draws all creation into the song that never stops.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chagar* (v.12, 'gird themselves') — to gird, to belt; the warrior's verb applied to hills robing themselves in joy. *Rua* (v.13, 'shout for joy') — the cultic triumphal shout; the same verb used of Israel's worship in the great assembly (Ezra 3:11; Psalm 47:1). *Shir* (v.13, 'sing') — the verb of Israel's definitive songs (Exodus 15:1; Judges 5:1); creation joins the song of Moses and Deborah."
